  </article>
<p>Alcohol content is measured by how much alcohol is in a given amount of =
an alcoholic beverage. Wine, beer, and cider are usually listed as alcohol =
by volume (ABV), and liquor (distilled spirits) is labeled by =E2=80=9Cproo=
f.=E2=80=9D</p><p>Alcohol proof for distilled spirits is equal to twice the=
 percentage of alcohol content by volume. For example, liquor that is 80 pr=
oof contains 40% alcohol by volume (ABV). For comparison, the average ABV f=
or beer is as low as 5% but can be higher than 10%. The average ABV for win=
e is 11-13%. This makes a difference when thinking about how much alcohol y=
ou consume and what it means for your blood alcohol concentration.</p><h4>S=
tandard drink size</h4><p>Knowing standard drink sizes will help you figure=
 out how much alcohol is in your drink. By knowing this, you can make safer=
 choices about how much you drink. One standard drink is defined as contain=
ing 0.6 ounces of pure alcohol.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>The chart below demonstra=
tes how the ABV varies depending on the type of alcohol. That means standar=
d drink sizes will also vary.</p><table><thead><tr><th>12 oz. beer</th><th>=
8-10 oz. malt liquor or flavored malt beverages like hard seltzer</th><th>5=
 oz. wine</th><th>1.5 oz. shot of distilled spirits (gin, rum, vodka, tequi=
la, whiskey, etc.</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Range from 5% to more tha=
n 10% alcohol</td><td>About 7% alcohol</td><td>About 12% alcohol</td><td>Ab=
out 40% alcohol</td></tr></tbody></table><h4>Calculating standard drinks</h=
4><p>Because of the differences in alcohol levels in various types of alcoh=
olic drinks,&nbsp; one =E2=80=9Cdrink=E2=80=9D may be more or less than a =
=E2=80=9Cstandard drink.=E2=80=9D You can find the number of standard drink=
s in a beverage by doing some simple math.</p><ul><li>The formula: the numb=
er of standard drinks =3D (volume) x (ABV) / 0.60<ul><li>Example:&nbsp; How=
 many standard drinks are in a 16-ounce beer with a 9% (.09) ABV?<ul><li>X =
standard drinks =3D 16 x .09 / 0.60</li><li>X =3D 2.4 standard drinks<br>&n=
bsp;</li></ul></li></ul></li><li>For alcohol labeled by =E2=80=9Cproof=E2=
=80=9D rather than as ABV (for example many distilled spirits are labeled a=
s 80% proof), find the ABV by dividing the proof in half (90 proof =3D 45% =
ABV).<ul><li>Let=E2=80=99s say you order a mixed drink cocktail that contai=
ns two different spirits for a total of 2.5 ounces of alcohol at 80 proof.<=
ul><li>X standard drinks =3D 2.5 x .40 / 0.60</li><li>X =3D 1.6 standard dr=
inks</li></ul></li></ul></li></ul><p>This <a href=3D"http://www.rethinkingd=
rinking.niaaa.nih.gov/tools/calculators/drink-size-calculator.aspx" target=
=3D"_blank" class=3D"ext" data-extlink=3D"" rel=3D"noreferrer"><strong>stan=
dard drink calculator</strong><svg focusable=3D"false" class=3D"ext" data-e=
xtlink-placement=3D"append" aria-label=3D"(link is external)" viewBox=3D"0 =
0 80 40" role=3D"img" aria-hidden=3D"false"><title>(link is external)</titl=
e><path d=3D"M48 26c-1.1 0-2 0.9-2 2v26H10V18h26c1.1 0 2-0.9 2-2s-0.9-2-2-2=
H8c-1.1 0-2 0.9-2 2v40c0 1.1 0.9 2 2 2h40c1.1 0 2-0.9 2-2V28C50 26.9 49.1 2=
6 48 26z"></path><path d=3D"M56 6H44c-1.1 0-2 0.9-2 2s0.9 2 2 2h7.2L30.6 30=
.6c-0.8 0.8-0.8 2 0 2.8C31 33.8 31.5 34 32 34s1-0.2 1.4-0.6L54 12.8V20c0 1.=
1 0.9 2 2 2s2-0.9 2-2V8C58 6.9 57.1 6 56 6z"></path></svg></a> can do the m=
ath for you.</p><h4>Why this is important</h4><p>The liver processes the al=
cohol content of one standard drink per hour. Tracking how many standard dr=
inks are being consumed can improve the ability to make responsible decisio=
ns and reduce the negative consequences of drinking too much alcohol.</p>
